                  <bindingDesc>
                     
                     <binding notAfter="1550" notBefore="1475">
                        
                        <p><note>Alexandra Gillespie observes that very few well-known vernacular manuscripts have survived in their medieval bindings and that MS. Rawl. D. 3 is one of only four 
                           of Chaucer’s works that has a pre-1500 cover. Gillespie names the other three Chaucer manuscripts as <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_8926">MS. Selden Supra 56</ref>,  
                           <ref target="https://www.medievalscribes.com/index.php?browse=manuscripts&amp;id=7&amp;nav=off">Cambridge, St John’s, MS E. 2</ref> and 
                           <ref target="https://www.medievalscribes.com/index.php?nav=off&amp;browse=manuscripts&amp;id=100">London, Institution of Engineering and Technology Library, MS Thompson 1</ref>
                           ('<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/434020/bodleian_library_western_medieval_manuscripts_bibliography/tags/MS.%20Selden%20Supra%2056/items/PFBRWD5R/item-list">Bookbinding</ref>' 
                           in <title>The Production of Books in England 1350–1500</title> ed. by Wakelin and Gillespie [Cambridge University Press, 2011], p. 158 and p. 165)
                        
                        </note></p>
                     </binding>
                     
